snippet.textDisplay: That's got to be a high power flat4 for sure.  They're 44IDFs with 36mm chokes which is pretty big, bigger than I ran on my RX3 with dual 40IDFs.  One day I saw an ad in a magazine on twin weber manifolds for 13bs so I thought I'd try it out.  I searched around and pulled a pair of 40IDFs second hand from a decent dirt/speedway VW and changed the chokes from 28 to 30.  The main reason why I think they're 44IDFs is the extended emulsion tube and blocked off cold engine 'choke/fuel circuit'.  If you want to learn about carbs like these, find a greybeard that used to run rotaries, VWs or Italian cars because Isaac looks busy :D

snippet.textDisplay: It's common to swap out an original 1600 for a 2000 engine from a bus, and probably even more common after seizing up your 1600 due to not checking the oil level that it gets bored/stroked to a larger displacement depending on which piston kit you bought. I've got a 4-seat buggy that originally had the stock 1600 single carb setup that was rebuilt as an 1835. So regardless of displacement, that twin carb setup with ported heads nods heavily to the early Porsche engines. Can't wait to see how she runs!
